unsigned id = 0;
if (!m_id_map.find(e, id)) {
     id = m_next_id++;
     m_id_map.insert(e, id);
}
return id;

I've got a preference for keeping the code inside `try:` minimal (only stuff that can actually raise a catchable error, in this case).  If it were a case of the API method returning a value we just pass through, then we could have:

```python
    try:
        return something_returning_boolean(args, go, here)
    except SomeError:
        return False
```

You could make a case for moving the `return True` to the outer function scope, but it seems cleaerst to have it "parallel" with the exception case.
